🧾 What I did in this experiment
In this experiment, I used Jenkins running inside Docker to generate and publish a reactive web page. I created a Pipeline job and added a Jenkins script that generated three files: index.html, style.css, and app.js. The JavaScript file maintained the page state and updated the content dynamically when the button was clicked, without reloading the page. After running the pipeline, Jenkins published the reactive web page inside the build page and archived all generated files as artifacts.

🎤 Viva explanation
I deployed Jenkins using Docker and created a Pipeline job to generate a reactive web page. The page was made reactive using JavaScript, which updated the displayed content when the user clicked a button. Jenkins published the generated page using HTML Publisher and archived the HTML, CSS, and JavaScript files as artifacts.

✅ Final statement
A reactive web page was successfully generated, published, and archived using Jenkins running in Docker.
